TEXT: (Interpreted).
Ladies and gentlemen, good morning.
Good morning.
We're delighted as always to have you this morning with Christophe Cros.
We are going to present the 2015 annual results for Suez.
First of all, I would like to thank those of you who came this morning and I would like to remind you that this presentation will be available through the webcast.
You will be able to download it as well from the Group's -- the Company's website.
Before getting started and commenting on the Company's performance, I would like to remind you that the Suez's activities is trying to address the challenges of this century.
We are very much engaged in the resource revolution.
During COP21, all players, both civil society, the corporate world were mobilized.
It was a turning point, a decisive event, during which Suez was actively present.
We're very proud to take part and feel that we can fully contribute by addressing the challenges of today's world with some of our technologies and solutions in order to save our planet.
My presentation will be as follows.
We will start off by a presentation on the 2015 performance.
And I can say that we are quite satisfied because we reached, even outperformed, our objectives.
This performance is based primarily on progress made by the Company in the commercial area.
We had a number of successes around the globe.
The results are remarkable, especially given the fact that the global context has been much more complicated than initially anticipated at the beginning of 2015.
Good morning.
As for 2016, well, I feel confident.
I feel confident because Suez is a very well-balanced company.
However, I think we have to become more vigilant.
There are uncertainties, geopolitical uncertainties, emerging countries, the production crisis in Europe, and we have to remain cautious.

And for that reason, we've decided to accelerate the transformation of Suez to make it a more integrated company, to make it a company able to address sustainable requirements and needs and manage resources in a more sustainable way going forward.
I will wrap up by giving you an overview of our financial performance for 2015.
So, before diving into the figures, I would like to come back to one important component of Suez's transformation throughout 2015.
The name, as you know, the name is now shared by all.
In the past we had 40 different brands.
And this is a significant sign of progress.
And we're now an integrated company and it is a sign for more collaboration between the employees.
And it is a sign as well of progress for our customers.
Since March 2015 we have all become ambassadors of the Suez brand and we are all firmly committed to become a benchmark in the industry.
Our visibility for the outside world has been significantly improved and increased, and we are already seeing benefits with recently signed contracts.
I would like to comment on two important external growth that happened in 2015.
As you know, with the Chongqing authorities in China, we have an agreement.
This is a company which is active in both water and waste treatment.
It is a very active region, the Sichuan region.
But it's not limited to that region only.
It's very active throughout China and in the region.
Another important operation is minority buyback of an Australian company, and with very good financial conditions.
And with this, we're going to be able to deploy an integration strategy which is the same strategy we've deployed around the globe.
This is the integration of our two activities, water and waste.
And we're going to obtain synergies both in terms of cost and from the commercial standpoint.
Regarding the financial performance in 2015, well, I can confirm that we have stuck to all our commitments.
We were able to improve the Company's profitability.
EBITDA is up 4.1%.
EBIT is up more than 10%.
And our net income Group share is EUR408m.
Free cash flow, which is a very important indicator, as you know, is above EUR1,047m, Christophe will comment on this.
And our financial flexibility has remained excellent with our net debt over EBITDA is 2.9 times.
We're going to ask the general assembly to pay a dividend of EUR0.65 per share.
So you will agree with me that these results are very satisfactory, once again, in a context which I would describe as complex.
We'll come back to this throughout the presentation.
Taking a look at the next slide, you will see what the -- where the commercial successes are coming from for 2015.
This is true for the entire Group and all the divisions.
Investment decisions are made centrally, however, our commercial policies are very much local.
So the 2015 success stories are the success stories of the people out there in the field.
I can't go through all the contracts.
Let me just give you a few starting off with water in France.
I'm very happy, very proud of the development of our new services.
An illustration of this would be the decarbonation, which is a way to soften water, with the Gennevilliers municipality, we have a contract.
We renewed the contract, which is a public delegation contract.
The value is EUR639m over a 12-year period.
We were also able to get the contract for water supply, so this is de-carbonated water supply, we have a EUR234m contract.
This is 15-year contract, to improve the quality of water, to secure the water supply to over 600,000 citizens living in the Gennevilliers area.

What is interesting with this new contract is that it perfectly illustrates the trust, how much our customers trust us, and our ability to roll out technologies, technological innovations, including in areas where we have operated for many years.
In waste, I would like to come back to the Covaldem 11 contract.
This is a contract which covers seven municipalities, including the Municipality of Carcassonne.
Total amount is EUR459m over a 19-year period.

It's a very innovative partnership, which brings together civil society and municipalities with a new governance model, which I would describe as the collective collaborative model, with different stakeholders, including Board level.
This is how this new partnership contract will be managed.
With this contract, we're going to become better at optimizing waste.
And the overall rate, reuse rate, will be much better than what we have so far.
So this is going to generate additional turnover, and once again, it illustrates that as a company we are becoming increasingly innovative.
This is the first contract, public service delegation contract.
We've never had anything like this in waste.
We've had it in incineration, but this is not an incineration contract.
It's a different contract.
So, another contract, another deal I would like to comment is -- as you can see, first of all, we've reinforced our positions across the globe.
This is very much the case in Asia.
China, as you can see, is a very promising and strong market.

The authorities are increasingly seeking to give a priority to environmental questions, and we have a new contract to pick up a 30-year contract for -- in Changshu for a, which is an industrial park, for wastewater treatment.
This makes it the 11th -- it's the 11th biggest wastewater treatment facility in China.
And it's an interesting contract because it's an area where chemical operators, chemical industries and fluoride is being processed and treated.
The last contract is the contract we picked up with Sanofi.
I've commented on this contract during the announcement of our half-year results.
And we -- there are additional contracts as well.
We have a multi-site contract which we just signed with Safran.
This is a EUR10m contract for a maximum length of five years.
And it includes waste management as well as treatment facility management for 11 sites.
Suez is -- will be identifying progress opportunities to better manage waste, waste reuse, metals, oils, wood, cardboard, plastic.
And we will significantly contribute to the company's footprint, Safran's footprint.
This is a beautiful example of a partnership and industrial partnership where Suez is providing all its experience and knowhow to a large company, Safran.
And as you probably know, we've had a joint venture with Safran and Airbus with tarmac near the city of Tarbes.
So these examples show how important it is to have industrial partnerships and how we've been able to address the needs of -- different needs of our customers.
So, once again the competitive environment has become more complex in the meantime.

No one anticipated 2015 would be such a complicated year with the geopolitical changes, a number of crises in Brazil, in Russia, for example, deflation in Western countries, world growth which is slower than expected, especially influenced by the slowdown of the Chinese economy and of course with the drop of raw -- in the price of raw materials.
The outlook is still pretty negative with some of our private and public customers in a number of developed countries.
And again, as I said, competition has become more complex with newcomers.
A number of Asian companies are starting to do business in the Middle East, for example, and they're now also interested in Europe, of course.
And a lot of the big players are restructuring in order to meet the new challenges.
In 2015, our activities were positively impacted by weather in France, in Spain, and even in Chile, with volumes sold above long-term averages, expected averages.
So you will agree, the economic context was not very favorable, and this was of course very much the case in France as well.
The level of industrial production in France is still behind what we had in 2008, whereas countries like Germany have really managed to catch up since the subprime crisis.
And there's more and more concern about risks, both with industrial companies and municipalities.
People are -- have become a lot more sensitive to [debt].
Therefore, investments have contracted.
Again this is very much the case with private companies as well as municipalities, people are very cautious and are giving priority to short term.
The competitive landscape hasn't really changed in France, but there is more and more pressure on margins in order to remain competitive.
And therefore, Suez has to pay more attention to productivity.
So in some more complex environments, it is necessary to take actions rapidly.
Our balanced strategy, cautious strategy is more than ever the right strategy to meet our objectives, once again.
So let's go through what have been our priorities for some time now, starting with our international priorities.
As you know, environmental concerns are growing around the world.
But the stability of the current system is not guaranteed.
And this is why we are very carefully picking, choosing where to invest and how to invest.
As you know, we are not exposed to the Brazilian or Russian risks.
We are not impacted by the slowdown of the Chinese economy.
As I said earlier, environmental concerns are a priority for the Chinese authorities.

And in the meantime, our activities in Australia, the US, Chile, Morocco, and again China, are growing at a good pace, anywhere between 6% and 8% on average, which we consider is a reasonable pace for midterm growth.
It's a good way to perform well.
And we're still continuing our development in other geographies.
India, for example, is a very promising economy and yet a very complex market, with tremendous environmental needs going forward.
We were pioneers in India.
We've been operating there since 1985.
We've built more than 200 water treatment facilities.
And right now we have three interesting contracts with the Municipality of Delhi, Bangalore and Mumbai.
The objective of these contracts is to improve the quality of the network, the quality of the service as well.
We have four contracts to build and operate wastewater treatment facilities.
And we've just bought up Driplex.
Driplex is one of the leaders in industrial water treatment.
Last but not least, there is the Middle East.
Recently we've been selected for a contract in Barka, Oman, to build -- to design, build and operate a desalination facility.
This is a 20-year contract.
Capacity is 280,000 cubic meters per day.
This will be the biggest desalination facility of -- in the area.
And it will supply the City of Muscat and its -- and the overall area included, which has approximately 700,000 inhabitants.
So again this contract shows that as a company we're able to deliver the right technology to meet the needs.
There is tremendous water stress in the area, and this clearly shows that we are becoming a key player in the area in the desalination industry.
Second area is the industrial development.
We are already very present with industrial companies, EUR5.5b in sales, all operations combined.
EUR1.7b is coming from key accounts or large companies, which represents approximately 10% of the overall sales.
Environmental regulations have become more and more stringent, and people are realizing that it is important to limit water consumption and raw material consumptions.
And the market of industrial customers has changed tremendously.
To make things simple, there are a number of things companies are doing.
I think COP21 again was a good illustration of how things are changing and how people are increasingly aware of the importance of protecting the planet.
And we're here to support them.
Our model is co-construction, co-construction in order to deploy the best solutions to optimize their resources.
Our solutions are reliable both for water and raw materials and meet the two challenges which is to secure resources and control costs.

We also would like to gradually integrate our knowhow in the industrial processes of our customers in order to give them the best solutions, the best technologies to achieve excellence in the area of environmental performance.

In wastewater treatment for example, to limit resources, whether it's in the chemical industry or mining industry, it's important to control your waste, your effluents with different technologies such as ozone or membranes for example.
We also have smart collection technologies to optimize the supply chain with IT, embedded IT, in all systems, real-time technology.
We have extremely modern solutions like what we do in Rotterdam for example, where we have a sorting system which sorts plastics, different-grade plastics for immediate reuse for industrial purposes.

So as you understand, we're becoming industrial partners and we're really trying to -- seeking to deploy our activities And with more proximity, more transparency and again the concept of co-construction, to better control the lifecycle of all products.
Commercial gains with different companies such as Sanofi, Safran.
We've also signed agreements with Arkema and Total Oil.
Again these illustrate how successful our proactive policies have been.
And we expect activity to grow by approximately 10% per year on average, and we expect to reach sales of nearly EUR3b by 2020.
Moving on to the third area now.
Third area has to do with beneficial reuse]and waste recovery at the heart of our performance.
This of course spells competitive edge in the future models of the circular economy.
And we've embraced this for a very long time basically and we've taken strategic positions in energy and recovery of materials as well.
In 2016 and 2017, we are going to commission four PFI plants in the UK -- Cornwall, West London, Merseyside and Surrey.
There'll be one in Poland, in Poznan.
Thereby increasing our annual treatment capacity by 1.2m tons.
In the Netherlands we've just commissioned a plastic recycling unit called QCP, Quality Circular Polymers.
It produces high-quality polymers, to the tune of 30,000 tons per year.
We're also confirming our leadership by working downstream on a commercial proposition that's constantly redesigned to meet the future needs of our clients.
For example, we use digital transformation in order to come up with new value propositions on a B2C basis.
And this will be the case in smart waste, for instance.
Now this constant quest for productivity has led us to believe that we will have to treat waste on a European scale.
I'm talking about hazardous wastes, alternative fuels, secondary raw materials, which will be managed at the scale of the European continent.
Above and beyond the obvious economies of scale, this organization will help us optimize the saturation of our plants and to offset ups and downs on the markets.
Moreover, the better coordination with all our teams gives access to more and larger clients, and therefore more sales opportunities for all our propositions.
The final area has to do with new water services.
The lack of inflation in Europe of course bears upon our tariff increase possibilities.

And in mature countries, of course, there is a kind of loss of steam, which is why we have to be more and more innovative moving forward, so we have to be innovative from a technical and commercial standpoint in order to continue to grow.
In 2012 we had set out new water services as being one of the four pillars of the Group's growth.
Now the segment accounts for roughly EUR350m in sales and its growth was 23% in fiscal 2015.
We've decided to go even further by organizing our business lines, so we have a new business line, for new solutions.
And we call that Advanced Solutions.
This entity is going to develop and integrate the distribution of its solutions, including digital solutions, to meet our clients' expectations.
I'm talking about both private and public clients worldwide based on all the commercial and sales forces of the Group.
The strategy will enable us to strengthen our existing portfolio, and we shall offer high added value solutions.
We're also seeking to innovate from a contractual standpoint.
Such was the case for the public service delegation in Dole where we introduced a new form of management called SEMOP.
It's a mixed-economy company that has a new status under French legislation.
We're the first operator to set that up.
The local authorities are thus involved in all the decisions made by the new entity, the SEMOP, and it decides what has to be done.
So we are also making inroads into the smart business.
Since the beginning of the decade we've set up 2.6m meters sold across Europe, not to mention what we're doing in our Vision centers in French territories notably, also in Spain by the way.
So there is technical innovation.
There's one technical innovation I'd like to point out, I appreciated very much and so did Segolene Royal, Biovalsan.
It's in Strasbourg, and we -- and there's reinjection into the natural gas deposit in the area.
It's technical innovation and it's going to be followed by quite a few more in 2016.
So you see our results, our development potential are evidence of the fact that our strategy is well-founded.
And let me remind you of our strategy, it is based on a principle of balance.

A balance between operations that are sensitive to the economic situation and operations that are not as sensitive to the economy, long-term contracts with investment obligations, or short-term engagements for service provision.
And we have contracts with worldwide coverage with business models that are suited to local specificities in the countries where we operate.
We are quite proud to be where we are.
In the past our Group was made up of roughly independent companies, but now we have an environment service group that's integrated.
We have a worldwide footprint and we share our expertise throughout our entities.

Given the situation of the economy the way things are going, I decided to go further, because there is indeed a gap between the conviction that I have, I'm convinced that there will be growing need for -- growing need for our service in the medium and long term, and in the short term of course the economic situation is quite gloomy, notably in France.
In order to move faster and farther, I've decided to use a single brand, Suez, in order to adjust the Group to a changing world.
The adjustment is aimed at four purposes.
I apologize.
First, we need to provide our customers, wherever they are in the world, with the same level of operational excellence.
The idea is quite straightforward.
We have to identify the best practices in our operations and we have to deploy them across the Group as fast as possible.
Secondly, we need to accentuate the selectivity of our investments.
We must prioritize commercial investments.
Also, we need to dynamically arbitrate between make or buy.
By so doing, we of course challenge the worthwhileness of making or buying certain specific types of equipment such as in the case of ozone where we are a global leader.
Finally, we have to appropriately allocate our capital.

We are quite sensitive to low capital-intensity projects, but we need to be wary of low margin and vulnerability toward our clients, which is why we carefully examine every new project and we offer wherever possible solutions with high added value.
Thirdly, we need to accelerate the implementation of solutions appropriate to France where we get one-third of our sales, in order to take into consideration specificities of France.
The economic situation is quite specific in France, I spoke about that.
Also there is an institutional change and the map of the French region has changed and larger metropolitan areas have been created under French legislation.
We're going to step up coordination between our operations.
We're going to fortify our commercial efforts in order to face up to new challenges.
We're going to better distribute our footprint.
And we're going to optimize the use of our knowhow and investments.
Fourthly, we are going to increase our cost cutting efforts.
Although we've already achieved significant savings in the past few years, we still have quite a lot of potential, quite a lot of room for improvement.
Our compass objective for the period from 2016 to 2017 has been stepped up by EUR300m.
So that is to say another EUR150m of these net cost savings are indeed sustainable and they are audited.
On the strength of the robustness of our model and the relevance of our strategy, Suez posted very good performance in fiscal 2015.

Despite the fact that the environment remains uncertain in 2016, especially in France, our aim is to achieve organic sales growth of at least 2% next year, in 2016, that is, an organic EBIT growth of at least that of sales, that is to say greater than 2%.
Against this backdrop, maintaining financial flexibility and cash generation remain priorities.
And our net debt over EBITDA ratio shall remain at around 3.
And free cash flow will be roughly EUR1b in fiscal 2016.
We're going to continue to serve dividend.
We're going to pay dividend of at least EUR0.65 per share.
For -- well, in 2016, finally, we are maintaining our goal EBITDA of at least EUR3b in 2017.
Now I give the floor to Christophe Cros who is going to give you the details of the financial performance of the Group in fiscal 2015.
Christophe, over to you.
(Interpreted).
Thank you, Jean-Louis.
Good morning, ladies and gentlemen.
I'm going to walk you through the key financial items that characterize the Company's financial performance in fiscal 2015.
On this first slide here, you have a summary of the key numbers.
I think it's fair to say that our performance is excellent.

All our objectives have been achieved, even exceeded, in an environment, as said by Jean-Louis, that was quite contrasted, in other words, more challenging, more difficult than anticipated a little over a year ago.
If we take a look at the top line, the best top-line number since the Company's IPO, you can see that the growth is strong, and it actually accelerated quarter after quarter.
You can also see an increase in operating margin, whether we're talking about EBITDA or EBIT.
Let me specify that in fiscal 2015, EBITDA and EBIT included EUR131m of the revaluation of our stake in Chongqing Water.
I will speak about that in a moment.
And there is a coincidence because there's disposal gains from our energy operations in Macau in 2014, another EUR129m.
So if you compared 2014 and 2015, the numbers are roughly the same, as you saw there.
And of course we consider that there's a scope of variation in our international division.
It does not contaminate the examination of our organic growth figures.

Now if we take a look at the way things have changed, well, in line with what we've announced, we're looking at a 0.3% increase in EBITDA, and our EBIT grew quite sharply, because if you exclude FX and scope, there's a 4.5% increase in EBIT, organically speaking.
This does reflect the improvement we saw in our operational performance.
Net result was EUR408m.
That's attributable profit, which reflects the operational performance of the Group and its improvement.
I shall also demonstrate that it does reflect cautious management of our balance sheet in an environment, especially in France, which is not really that buoyant.
Things are pretty gloomy to say the least.
Now if you take into consideration the compensation of hybrid securities, the EPS, we're looking at [539m euro] shares, in 2015 we're looking at EUR0.69 per share.
We have a robust balance sheet and it does afford financial flexibility, which remains intact in 2015.
There was strong cash generation, well above that of 2014.
I'll speak about that in a moment.
We were very selective and active in our investments.
There's a rise in investments.
And the increase in net investments does primarily mirror the 40% buyback of 40% of our minority stakes recycling in Australia.
We bought out a minority interest.
The investment was EUR312m, AUD485m.
Of course, there is a -- there are currency swings there.
Net debt EUR8m, 2.9 times EBITDA, below the 3 mark we set, well, we set at the time of the IPO.
And ForEx amount -- the impact ForEx was above EUR300m, EUR326m and that hit the debt and it pushed the debt up.
Such are the key numbers that allow me to say that we have met our objectives and performance was, indeed, quite strong.
Let me break this performance down into a number of indicators.
Let me begin with the top-line sales increased, 5.7%.
And if you exclude ForEx and scope effects organic growth was 2.7%.
Let me try to anticipate a question you may have.
We headed out -- we were going for 3% growth, but there was a strong impact of ForEx and during fiscal 2015 and things accentuated over time.
We did have to face up to a drop in the price of commodities and there are two that are very sensitive to the price of ferrous metals, which dropped.
Paper didn't -- performed well and the price of electricity, which also dropped.
And the drop in these two commodities accounts for a 0.6% impact on organic growth.
So, if you restate for that, we would be above the initial objective which we had set ourselves.
Now, these developments account for the variations we have in our divisions.
As you can see, when it comes to sales, the dynamics are very strong in our international operations division.

And each one -- and each entity, in each country, in each geography that contribute to international operations, shows the relevance of the choices we have made and the lack of exposure we have in areas where there are -- where there is headwind.
I think it's fair to say that water Europe had a very good year.
There was a EUR142m increase in that division.
And that reflects very good, interesting performance of volume in France, Spain and Chile.
And it also shows that there's additional volume due to auspicious weather conditions.
Also there were price hikes in all three countries.

Although, as I shall say later, since we are sometimes nearing deflation, notably in France, well, by definition the lower the inflation the more the tariff index systems give results that are lower and lower; in other words, a drag on escalation.
So, you can see the 1.1% rise in the waste recovery business in Europe.

And, interestingly, if you exclude the price of raw materials, ferrous metals and electricity, as I said, for the first time in quite a few years organic growth was 0.2%, very low, of course, but above zero.
The little table you have at the bottom here shows you the gradual increase in our growth.
Of course, there are a few specific explanations that can be given.
Of course, the Q3 results do include very auspicious weather conditions or very warm summer in Spain and France.
But even if you restated for that, there would be an intensification in our organic growth in operations quarter after quarter.

And there's a very slight dip in Q4, as you can see, but it does not really affect what I just said because it just reflects the phasing of major construction work we have in our international operations.
I'm talking about Hong Kong and China where we have a lot going on in construction.
But this, of course, has nothing to do with what I'm saying about the growth has been accelerating.
There is significant ForEx impact.
We are, indeed, amplifying our international operation as far as scope is concerned, while there's the contribution of the selective acquisitions that we've been conducting.
We've acquired companies that provide us with complementary -- actually process with Poseidon or with the BV Group that we had already announced a while ago.
So much for sales.
Let me now move on to EBITDA.
As you can see, it has changed in line with our expectations, expectations we announced a year ago.
The impact of ForEx amounts to EUR83m on EBITDA simply has to do with the US dollar and the Chilean peso.
Regarding scope, that doesn't show, because the two numbers are quite identical from 2014 to 2015.
But there was the step-up in our stake in Chongqing Water in the Deron entity.
So, if you take the EUR2m gap that remains there remains EUR16m, the contribution of the acquisitions we made and contribution on EBITDA.
So, organic growth in EBITDA is 0.3%.
As you may recall, last year we said that this is lower than the organic EBIT growth.
And it does reflect the assumption that we had made, which proved true, that we would have spending and there were provisions, so there's no impact on EBIT, spending to the tune of EUR50m.
We'll give you the details of all this.
You can see this in the appendices, there that were EUR45m as planned.
And this reflects specific expenditure for the shutdown of landfill, specific spending for a packaging recycling system in Germany.
And in Australia there was a change in public policy and actually we had to pay back carbon tax, so there was a turnaround there.
So, the EUR45m in expenditure has to be compared with the assumption that we had shared with you, which was EUR50m.
Now, if we take a look at EBITDA with a breakdown by division, well, it reflects the trends that I described in sales.
It also shows the distribution, the geographic distribution, of the spending that had been planned.
The very outstanding performance of water Europe needs to be pointed out.
This is intrinsic performance - mark my words - France, Spain and Chile.
And it is spiked by the highly positive marginal contribution of additional volume recorded this summer -- last summer.
I'll show you in a moment that this has led to a change in our assumption, whereas, we had planned a drop in volume.
So, waste recovery EBITDA can be seen here, EUR45m spent.
So, if you take into account the minus EUR30m that can be seen here you can see that there's an offset, because we are still pursuing efficiency and productivity plans in this division.
Regarding the international division, variation shows the trends that we indicated in June and that we confirmed in late September.
The growth is quite small, lower than that of sales, as far as EBITDA is concerned.
While we have to first consider the carbon tax in Australia, and there is a change characterized by an increasing number in very large calls for tenders.

And so we have call-for-tenders-related expenses that are smaller than in the past but it does reflect the vitality of the business, the buoyancy of the business, that Jean-Louis alluded to a moment ago.
So, this shows that organic EBITDA has increased less than sales.
Now, if we take a look at the next slide, we're talking about EBIT now, and this gives you quite a reflection of the performance.
And, as you can see, the organic growth in EBIT is 4.5% above our objective for our EBIT.
So, we're looking at 10%.
And from EBITDA to EBITA there is a slight increase in amortization, a slight dip in renewal expenses.
And this is a demonstration of the improvement of our operational efficiency.
And I need to underscore that, once again, each and every division in the Group has given a positive contribution to the organic growth in EBIT.
Therefore, we once again have this three-pronged improvement, sales, EBIT and EBITDA.
So, as a percentage of sales, the EBIT margin once again rose.
And, as you can see, it's 10.1%, as shown here --  no, 9.1%, excuse me, EBITDA margin versus 8.8%.
So, once again, EBIT against sales has risen.
Now, these good operational results also reflect the continuation of the discipline, which shows the entrepreneurial spirit of our teams.
And also shows the dynamics that we've been pursuing to constantly seek efficiency and productivity gains.
And we call this the Compass plan, as you know.
We have further demonstrated these dynamics, because over the past four years, including 2014, we've achieved EUR620m in savings, net savings.
And 2015 we saved the equivalent of 1% of our operational spending.
So, 2015 was a very good year, in that regard.
It was necessary, by the way, because the environment was quite challenging.
And that was one of the reasons for which in the second half we intensified these efforts.
As you can see, we got EUR180m in savings in 2015.
Our aim was EUR150m.
We had announced this.
It was part and parcel of the EUR400m objective from 2015 to 2017.
As you can see, the consolidation or the fortification took place in H2 with the effort step-up we accomplished.
Also if we take a look at the distribution of these savings and additional efficiency gains, well, the distribution by nature shows the evolution that we had given you.
And it does respond to a question of yours.
Is there a risk of exhaustion here?

The answer is no, because little by little there is a shift towards a new area of possible savings in certain areas of the Group where we have not really tapped into, notably when it comes to procurement.
And procurement-related gains accounted for 35%, 30%, last year and this is in line with the change that we had directed your attention to.
Another source of satisfaction is that every division can -- has contributed to achieving these results.
And, as in previous years, the contribution is quite balanced.

Given this performance and given our necessary caution that Jean-Louis described for 2015 and 2016 we, therefore, consider that we are in a position to achieved EUR450m in savings this three-year plan of ours.
This aim includes the additional savings from 2015 and, of course, the outlook will be better for 2016 and the year thereafter, that's 2017.
Now a few words about the features of the performance of our three key divisions and let me give you a more detailed overview.
Let me begin with water Europe.
As you can see on this slide here, we achieved an excellent performance, which was intrinsic and then it became sparkling given the help of the weather.
Now, the weather wasn't identical in France, Spain and Chile, but the summer was warm.
As far as sales were concerned we benefited from a volume step up.
As you can see on the right here this is different from long-term trends.
We continue to assume that on an average volume in Spain drops a little over 1% per year.
But we did not experience that in 2015 in France at all, as you can see.
Above and beyond volume, there is an impact of prices that can be seen in all three countries.
It's particularly the case in Chile, 6.8%.
You see that on the right of the table as well here.
And you have the natural drag of the five-year revision that we benefited from in 2014 and the indexing scheme, the ability to continue to hike prices in Chile.
In France, as you can see, prices rose 2.6% on average.
No, I'm talking about Spain, excuse me, also very satisfactory.
And in France we're looking at 0.4% which is pretty good.
But this does show the kind of inertia; the lower the inflation the lesser the indexing, proportionally speaking.
Interestingly, also, when you take a look at the performance of water Europe in 2015 the sales situation shows a neutral balance for our concession operations.
This reflects the fact that in the current environment there's greater pressure exerted on prices due to the indexing schemes.
And also due to the fact that our public clients who lack public finance, then they are more and more cautious and painstaking when it comes to investment.
So, what they want is more money for their bucks, so to speak, which is legitimate.
And we do sense the impact of that.

Actually, this is more than offset by the fact that we have very strong dynamics in demand for our new services because the sales of new services, with high added value, jumped no less than 23% on the whole.
Let's take a lot at the EBIT, which is the best indicator to reflect our performance.
You see that the -- all this plus the impact of our operational efficiency efforts have made it possible to once again have an increase in the EBIT 60 basis points versus sales.
Now let me move on to the key features of recycling and recovery in Europe for 2015.

I think it's fair to say the performance was very satisfactory because, given the macroeconomic backdrop I described the situation is interesting, because there is starker and starker contrast from one country to the next.
Jean-Marc and I constantly see that the Netherlands are stepping away from an economic recession.
In the UK the economic performance has been pretty good.
And, of course, things are still pretty gloomy in France.
2015 was imbued with a drop in the price of raw materials, notably, two of which that we're sensitive to, either because we treat]a lot of ferrous metals.
We're not really concerned by non-ferrous metals.
And there was also a drop in the price of electricity.

And it's not so much the drop of the price of electricity on the markets, but there was the fact that the fixed-tariff contract that most operators had started to rely on 15 years ago is now less and less true.
Anyway, sales were up 0.5 a percentage point and down 1.1% organically and you can see the breakdown here on this table.
Let me show two untoward factors.
First of all, the further drop in volume in France with landfilling and so on, minus 3.4% in France.
This, of course, softened towards the end of the year.
On March 31, 2015, the quarterly trend was double digit, basically.
And the second untoward factor had an impact of roughly EUR80m on sales of division and this is the drop in the price of raw materials, commodities.
But, at the same time, I think we have to bear in mind that there are many elements that show that things are looking up.
First of all, volume has been sluggish in France.
But volume is doing much better in Benelux and in the UK.
So, if you restated for France, volume growth would be greater than zero.
Of course, it's small, granted, but it's different from what we had in the past.
Another favorable factor, in the UK we have continued to commission new production capacities resulting from the commercial successes of the PFIs.
And which means that with these very complex and large facilities we have been able to run them according to schedule and according to budget.
Also last year we said that we were worried about the economic situation in France and that there would be a price war waged by certain operators.
But that did not happen actually and that's good news.
As a matter of fact, the price of services in the UK and in Benelux -- it's a favorable trend.
Another favorable factor, as you can see we're at 1.9%, which is very near the two tonnes recycled biological and so on for every tonne disposed of.

So, in other words, the increasing volume we have in our recovery and recycling processes are more than offsetting the drop in volume disposed of, notably with the end of the landfilling program in the UK.
Final item here and you can see the EBIT margin.
Well, you can see a 40-basis point increase there in spite of all these facts.
And, given the necessary and efficient productivity plans and efficiency plans conducted in the division, we have been able to have this increase.
And so, it's more than resilience, if you ask me.

Now, moving on to international operations, the first characteristic that needs to be pointed out is the strong dynamics in demand from all our clients in all countries, whether the mature OECD countries where we have operations, say the US or Australia, but developing countries as well.
Demand was strong and this has contributed to a very good performance, because we have met the demand with commercial successes, hence, the top-line growth 17% on a growth basis, and 9% organically.
This strong growth across the board can also be seen in the excellent increase in our backlog, 13% increase in 2015 to EUR1.3b.
Gross EBIT increased 9%.

As in 2014, in this division, since increased the gains from Macau, there was the revaluation of our stake in Chongqing Water with the set up of the Deron Environment that we have -- that we can influence so this is an application of the IAS 28 standard.
We had already pointed out the contrast between strong sales and EBIT performance, which is a contrast due to a base effect.
In 2014 we had short-term contracts - very profitable contracts - in Iraq, for instance.
So, of course, the comparatives are rather untoward.
And there was an increase in the unit cost and the -- our tendering costs have increased.
So, we are starting up large projects.
You saw me mention Barka a moment ago.
So, this does not yet generate any margin, obviously.
But all this primarily accounts for this offset in time but things will, of course, be ironed out over time.
Such are the key features of our divisions.
Now let me continue to present the other items in the P&L, moving on from EBITDA to the result of operations from EBITDA to EBIT.
I believe that everything is [nominal], as they say in Houston, because things are quite consistent over time.
You can see amortization slightly up.
It's only due to FX, notably in Chile and the US.
I mentioned that a moment ago.
As far as a positive balance of provision carry-forwards, of course, we have used provisions to neutralize the non-recurring expense items under EBITDA as announced.
So, on the whole, the first indicator, you can see a double-digit increase in EBIT of which 4.5% organically.
Moving on to, well, from EBIT to operating activities on the first line you can see the re-branding cost.
Let me point out that there is a slight lag based on our budget.
But if you may recall that this was a two-step approach during the year.
So, I can confirm that the total cost has not changed, EUR60m, it's just the phasing between 2015 and 2016 which is different.
Also you can see that we have EUR71m of restructuring costs.
This reflects the intensification of what is going on, notably in recycling and recovery in Europe, intensification of the programs that had been initiated in the first half.
And it reflects the acceleration that Jean-Louis described.
At the same time, on the next line, you can see that we wrote up EUR74m of provisions on assets.
This all reflects our will to be flexible.
It has to do with a large number of small items.
No item is over EUR10m.
But, essentially, focus is on recycling and recovery in Europe, especially in France.
So, these two items were possible, not absolutely necessary, but it was possible.
And this, of course, is going to contribute to further recovery in our operating margin, either by reducing direct cost, or by achieving amortization-related savings.
Let me preempt one of your questions maybe on these amounts with respect to the revaluation of our stake in Chongqing Water.
Indeed, things are coincidental.
Let me be nice and clear.
On the whole the result of operating activities did rise; the second indicator after EBIT.
So, as you can see, income from operating activities grew 2.1% organically, 2.9% on a reported basis.
Moving on from income from operating activities to net result, net attributable profit, as you can see once again there is a drop in the cost of debt of 4.45% from 4.45% to 4.19%.
This, of course, reflects the lower interest rates.
But you need to actively and efficiently manage your debt.
As you know, we went through quite a few steps.
We managed hybrid securities.
We issued a 10-year bond with a rate of 1.862% over 10 years which, of course, shows the quality of our signature and the very good and efficient management of our debt.
Also, as you may recall, in another -- under financial interest there were provisions for long-term monitoring and management of landfilling.
And this, of course, takes into account the discounted value.
As you can see, our income tax is well managed, both the amount - the amount remains very flat, EUR173m - and the rate is 33.3% versus 30%.
So, you can see the EUR614m in net profit.
Minority interest increased somewhat.
Of course, this is not very intuitive because, of course, there's the reduction of the minority interest in Spain because of our increased stake in one of our operations in Spain.
And this increase in minority interest reflects what happened in Chile with the peso, of course.
And in 2014, as we explained, there was a variation in corporate income tax there.
So, on the whole, our net attributable profit amounted to EUR408m in fiscal 2015.
I recognize that mathematically speaking it's EUR9m less than last year.
But I do hope that you will have noted two things.
First, in 2015 there was spending for the re-branding and this is new from 2014.

But, more importantly, based on the very good performance of organic EBIT and very good operational activities and results before minority interest, it's quite clear that our underlying profit improved in 2015 from 2014.
Now looking at cash generation, another source of satisfaction; let me begin with CapEx.
Net investments amounted to EUR1.600m in fiscal 2015, up from 2014.
It can be broken down as follows.
Maintenance CapEx follow very good discipline in line with top-line growth.
And then you have development CapEx.
This reflects large contracts that we took in or highly profitable CapEx.
This means regulated water operations in Chile and the United States.
So, these are development CapEx items that auger well for the increase in the Company's profitability, moving forward.
And, finally, there are financial investments.
And this includes the buyback of our 40% minority interest in Australia and small technology tuck-in acquisitions that I alluded to earlier.
So, we were very selective once again in 2015, but there were stronger vitality in our investments.
We were able to achieve such investments.
But, at the same time, as you can see, we also considerably stepped up our cash flow and free cash-flow generation because free cash flow amounted to EUR7m.
The amount was relatively the same last year, but the capital gains on the disposal of energy operations in Macau was cash but for Chongqing water revaluation it was not.
So, there was quite a step-up in cash generation in 2015.
There's one key contributor that we're very happy with, because there was virtually no impact of the variation of working capital requirement.
And this reflects the strong discipline that we've had for [DPO and SO] of our teams.
So, very -- we're very happy with that.
And this actually allows us to look at our net debt, a little over EUR8b at the end of fiscal 2015.
I think this can be summarized with three comments.
First of all, the increase in our physical investments that I spoke about a moment ago.
Secondly, there's a significant impact of ForEx, EUR326m.
And the third item, of course, is within financial investments there's the buyback of the 40% that were previously held by SembCorp in Australia.
So, at 2.9 times EBITDA, very much in line with our objective.
Our objective is no more than 3.
And we also wish to have a very good financial rating.
So, in net debt there are EUR2.8b in liquidity on December 31.
I'll spare you the details.
I spoke about a very active and efficient management.
That's very good indeed.
One final word about capital employed and the profitability of capital employed, return on capital employed.
As you can see, ROCE increased to 7.9% in fiscal 2015.
And this is quite interesting, because the increase was on the stability of ROCE from last year.
As far as the international operations are concerned, very high level for that.
And there was an increase in ROCE in the two other divisions.
At the same time, the average weighted cost of capital was stable, 6.3%.
This shows that if we measure things like that value creation did indeed increase in fiscal 2015.
On the left you have the breakdown of capital employed, EUR14.8b.
The increase from EUR14.1b is due to two key items, first of all ForEx, [EUR386m] and the logical impact of the re-evaluation of our stake in Chongqing Water.
At this point I would like to remind you that within capital employed, as in previous years, we are maintaining fixed assets, EUR200m.
It's the assets under construction which, by definition, have not generated anything in 2015.
Such are the key items that I wanted to share with you.

Jean-Louis and I believe that as far as the financial performance of the Company is concerned they're quite representative and they do show that we can move on in 2015 with a lot of confidence, although there may be some headwind here and there on our journey.
I'll hand over to Jean-Louis who's going to give you a conclusion and then I'll be happy to entertain your questions.
(Interpreted).
Well, my conclusion will be brief.
I think you're able to appreciate our results, the results we've just analyzed in front of you.
I consider them personally as remarkable intrinsically.
First of all, they show that our business model more than ever makes sense.
We've been able to reach our objectives in spite of unexpected and more complex context in the economy.
I think we were able to reinforce the fundamentals of the Company.
We were able to accelerate the transformation of Suez to make it a more integrated-service company.
The unique, single objective is to always better serve our customers.
One of our key advantages is that we operate in an industry where there is growing demand for services, the services we offer.
Of course, the demand is changing.
It is not the same from one country to another, from one industry to another.
But we consider there is a huge potential.
And I think that most actions taken by companies and the decisions made by companies, including during COP21 are strong testimonial of this.
Our job is to once again better serve the customers.
And, of course, to better protect and defend the interests of our planet.
For 2016, our priorities will be to improve our performance, to further develop our activities in integrated solutions, integrated offers, to better meet our customers' demand.
We will remain selective when it comes to choosing projects and bids.
And we will continue to be financially disciplined.
So, with a lot of uncertainty in the economy and the world situation we consider there are many opportunities.
There are four reasons for us to be confident for 2016.
First of all, we're going to reinforce our commercial momentum.
Second, we're going to further control our costs.
Third, we're going to become more competitive.
And, fourth, we're going to remain financially disciplined.
Thank you very much for your attention.
I think we can now answer your questions with Christophe and the entire team.

I think we can start questions on the phone and then we'll take questions from the audience here.

I have repeatedly said that we could conduct acquisitions, small acquisitions or mid-sized acquisitions, and we actually showed this year that some of these acquisitions made sense in a number of countries including in developing countries.

I also said that we thought it made sense to conduct acquisitions in mature economies where we have strong teams, countries we're familiar with, countries where we have experience and where we consider we can generate synergies.
And, again, this remains unchanged since I said this last year when I told you about our strategy.

(Interpreted).

Christophe?
(Interpreted).

Regarding the impact of ForEx in our guidance, well, as we speak, currency swings have been measured, apart from sterling, and we're looking at a little over EUR1b in capital employed in the UK.

So, it is going to be a negative impact which I cannot quantify for you, unless you give me the rate of sterling that you wish to use and I can crunch the numbers for you and give you EBIT and EBITDA.
But I can't do that if you -- without that rate.

(Interpreted).

The Suez Board approved my strategy and it's been based on the development of two core businesses for eight years, two core businesses that are essential for the lives of citizens for the next decades.

How have you hedged the price variations?

We have a number of existing contracts.
I mentioned the Sanofi one, which is just one example.
I also mentioned a number of other key accounts with whom we've signed mid-term and long-term contracts, five-year contracts, for example.
And all these contracts are giving us the figures we describe earlier.
The same thing's true for public service delegation and water.
There are two types of contracts.
We have different types of contracts.
4-, 5-, 10-year contracts, variable contracts.
And with -- then we have Sanofi contracts, where you have long-term contractual relationships with partners.
And as we go, we have more contracts that come in.
Take Sanofi, for example.
With Sanofi, I think we're currently executing about EUR50m in contracts with Sanofi and we have a pipeline which is much above that figure for the years to come.

We produce power and we are a net producer through energy from waste in the UK.
The same thing's true in Belgium and the Netherlands.
Our hedging strategy is natural hedging.
In Belgium, for example, we product steam and turbine electricity.
Jean-Marc took an initiative two years ago to do natural hedging in France.
Just to give you the magnitude, if you have 1.5 terawatts per hour which you buy and sell, well the question was can't we offset the two?
And back then the answer was no, because we're still benefiting from the fixed tariffs.
And they had -- these were valid for 15 years.
So it was better to sell the power at a very good price and then buy power.
Again, we had hedging.
The water sector is a big consumer.
So today, with the expiration of these contracts in France, as we are speaking, we are examining what we can do towards -- to go towards this natural hedging system.
(Interpreted).
Good morning.
I would like to come back to the first question of the analyst from Citi, the bridge between now and 2017, the EUR3b.
There are a lot of stock market valuations.
But when you look at the assets, how much pressure is there on asset valuation?
So what are the things you look at when you look at potential assets?
And why not take the opportunity of price declines, GDP, for example, and others?
Don't you think this isn't an opportunity to maybe review your EUR3b figure?
(Interpreted).
Well, I don't see why I should change my ambition if raw materials are going down.
Regarding asset valuation, your question's a difficult question.
Listed assets have -- some have declined.
But then at the same time, others have remained stable.
Globally I think that the value of assets is lower than what it used to be simply five or six years ago, no doubt.
I suppose it depends on the buyers and who's buying and who's selling.
I think there are a lot of discrepancies when you look at the markets.
Again, we're quite selective.
Once again, we're not going to do anything, just anything to reach our EUR3b objective.
We will be very focused.
However, if and when there are opportunities, we have to gauge them very carefully.
